A £2 daily dose of medication reduces the risk of a heart attack
Officials have suggested that thousands of heart patients would benefit from a £2-a-day drug that would be rolled out to more patients and taken for longer periods of time.
The anticoagulant ticagrelor reduces the risk of heart recurrence in people with heart disease.
This medication, taken for 12 months after a heart attack, reduces the risk of a stroke or another heart attack.
The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE), the UK's national health service (NHS) regulator, recommends that patients continue to take the medication for four years to further reduce the risk of cardiovascular disease.
But now, the NHS regulator NICE recommends that patients continue to take the drug for four years to further reduce the risk of cardiovascular disease.
Around 140,000 people in England suffer from heart disease each year, and a quarter of them go on to experience heart recurrences or strokes.
Heart attacks and strokes are caused by fatty substances deposited in the walls of arteries to form plaques.
If the plaque breaks, it can cause a blood clot, which in turn blocks blood flow to the heart and leads to a heart attack.
If the blood clot moves, it enters the bloodstream and blocks blood flow to the brain, leading to a stroke.
People who have already experienced a heart attack have a higher risk of having another heart attack.
Manufactured by the British company AstraZeneca and marketed under the brand name Brilique, ticagrelor reduces the risk of developing blood clots by reducing the formation of blood clots.
The draft NICE guidance, released today, recommends that patients take ticagrelor 90 mg daily for 12 months, followed by 60mg of ticagrelor and aspirin twice daily for the next three years.
Professor Carole Longson, Director of the NICE Centre for Health Technology Assessment, said: "Despite effective secondary prevention treatments, up to a quarter of patients who have had a history of heart attack will have a recurrence or stroke, often with serious consequences. ”
The fear of relapse can have a big negative impact on a person's quality of life.
Evidence suggests that ticagrelor when taken with aspirin is effective in reducing the risk of heart recurrence and stroke in those who have experienced a heart attack.
We are pleased that the interim referral of ticagrelor will provide more treatment options for thousands of people who have benefited."
Due to limited information on the efficacy and safety of ticagrelor after three years, particularly the risk of bleeding, the draft guidance does not recommend continued treatment beyond this period.
