China's Mars program is coming
China's Mars exploration mission must orbit, land, and patrol at one time, which has never been done in foreign countries.
China's Mars exploration and launch goal is to orbit, land, and patrol in one step, and this task is quite difficult.
Because it takes 26 months for Mars exploration to encounter a time window, experts are working engineering plans to launch China's first Mars rover in 2020.
According to Xu Dazhe, although China's aircraft have entered deep space, it is still indispensable to complete the Mars exploration mission, which means that China has entered the era of deep space exploration in a real sense.
"Every two or three years, there is only one chance that Mars is closest to Earth, and launching a Mars rover at this point in time is the most energy-saving for the launch vehicle. ”
"Considering the mass of the Mars probe, the launch mission will be completed by China's Long March 5 carrier rocket. ”
China's Mars exploration mission has to achieve orbiting, landing, and patrol at one time, which has never been done in foreign countries, and foreign countries have planned to achieve orbiting and landing at one time, but the landing has failed.
Mars exploration involves many technical fields, and the special thing is that although the rover is a space probe, it has distinctive characteristics compared with ordinary space probes.
In other words, the Mars rover must have the ability to determine the route and detect the danger of obstacles.
Pang Zhihao, a researcher at the Fifth Academy of China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation, said that the reason why mankind is so interested in Mars exploration is because Mars exploration has important scientific, technological and other significance, and is even related to the future of mankind.
At present, Mars has become the planet with the highest degree of human research except the Earth, and the history of human exploration of Mars using space probes runs through almost the entire history of human spaceflight.
Therefore, humanity hopes to one day establish a living base on Mars, and eventually migrate to Mars, turning it into a second home for humans.
There are also plenty of indications that Mars may well have been like the Earth today, with a thin atmosphere, cooler temperatures, and depleted water sources after billions of years of evolution.
Therefore, the exploration or manned landing on Mars for research can put forward a plan to prevent the Earth from becoming a second Mars that is difficult for humans to live on.
As of June 2016, there have been 114 lunar explorations and 43 Mars explorations around the world.
However, from the 90s of the 20th century to the present, humans have carried out a total of 18 Mars explorations, while the Moon has only carried out 14 explorations.
There are currently 5 Mars orbiters and 2 Mars rovers in operation, but only 1 lunar orbiter and 1 lunar lander are working.
The world's space powers have formulated exploration plans aimed at the Mars system, which shows that today's Mars exploration is hotter than the lunar exploration.
On November 5, 2013, India launched its first Mars rover, Mangarien, becoming the first country in Asia to successfully explore Mars.
Mangarion is used to study the surface, atmosphere and mineral characteristics of Mars, and to find out if there is methane and signs of life on Mars.
The most difficult part of this mission is that after the probe enters the Martian atmosphere, the aerodynamic shape and parachute deceleration only have one chance
According to Sun Zezhou, chief designer of the Mars rover of the Fifth Academy of China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation, the Mars exploration mission faces many technical challenges.
The Martian atmosphere pressure is very low, only 1% of the atmospheric pressure on the Earth's surface, and has a high degree of uncertainty.
Scientists do not yet have a thorough understanding of its changes and its storm-time behavior.
Mars often forms dust storms similar to Earth's dust weather in the summer, which can cause a sharp drop in the amount of sunlight energy received by the rover, and the rover must be designed to "sleep" and let it patiently wait for the dust storm to pass.
At the same time, the Martian atmosphere also has a reducing effect on solar light, which brings problems to the energy supply of Mars exploration.
This requires the probe to have a larger solar wing and to constantly adjust and try to align with the sun.
Also, the gravity on the surface of Mars is only 38% of that of Earth, but much more than the gravity of the surface of the Moon, so the probe needs more power.
"The core and most difficult part of this Mars exploration mission is the aerodynamic shape and parachute deceleration process of the probe after entering the Martian atmosphere. ”
Sun Zezhou said that due to the distance between the Earth and Mars, the whole process cannot be controlled by the ground in real time, so it must be completed independently by the probe.
Since there is not as much propellant to counteract such high speeds, the deceleration of landing on Mars depends on the action of the Martian atmosphere, which is difficult to simulate on the ground.
Pang Zhihao said that in general, the way of exploring Mars is similar to the way of exploring the moon, which is also "orbiting, landing, patrolling, and returning", and finally achieving the goal of manned landing on Mars.
Because Mars is much farther away from Earth than the Moon is from Earth, exploring Mars requires a more complex set of technical hurdles to overcome.
