Grecia is a cute female toucan that reeks of the rainforest.
In the Central American country of Costa Rica, the toucan Grecia and its story have long been a household name.
At a press conference on August 10, the recovering Grecia finally made an appearance to show off her brand new 3D-printed plastic beak.
The toucan, whose beak was broken off a year and a half ago, is finally reborn.
This day is not only a declaration that it is 100% healthy, but also a day when it moves into a luxury aviary and meets its caring human friends.
Grecia was a little shy when she first entered her new home, but after a while she became lively, rolling and frolicking in the basin and eating grapes with her new beak.
To remind people of the injuries it had suffered, technicians did not color its new beak, but instead kept the original white color of the 3D printed material.
The beak is a thin sheath with a hollow inside, with only a few thin bony support rods staggered.
Despite this internal reinforcement, toucans' beaks are fragile and shatter when damaged.
Animal rescue centers, ornithologists and an American 3D printing company worked together to create several "test beaks" for Grecia, and finally created the "perfect beak" that suited her.
Today, Grecia is adept at using her new beak to drink, eat, and even peck at tiny grains.
"The final design took about two months, and it only took four or five hours to print. ”
"3D printing is not the technology of the future, it has really entered your life. Thomas Lange, chairman of SG3D printing company in the United States, said in an interview with Xinhua International reporters.
In January 2015, Grecia, a bloodied toucan, was found on a farm in Grecia, in the department of Alajuela in central Costa Rica.
At that time, its upper beak was brutally broken by a group of young people, and it was completely unable to eat and was dying.
When the media reported on the tragic situation of Grecia, it caused a wave of voices against animal cruelty in Costa Rica and beyond.
There are calls for stricter animal protection laws and greater penalties for abusers.
People came spontaneously and did their best to help Grecia recover as much as possible from her pre-injury life.
Even Chuck Hull, the inventor of 3D printing, was involved in the design of Grecia's upper beak.
"Grecia was in a special situation, with less than 1 centimeter of the upper beak remaining, so it made it difficult to install a new beak. ”
"We scanned Grecia, then designed and fabricated an extension prosthesis that was slightly longer than the rest of its upper beak and attached it to its upper beak with adhesive. ”
"This would reduce the amount of further invasive harm to Gracia. Lange & Söhne told Xinhua International reporters.
Before the implant was fitted, the staff had to clean Grecia's severed beak every day to prevent infection.
Thousands of miles away, the story of Grecia the toucan touched famed documentary filmmaker Paula Heredia and Discovery News Channel producer John Hoffman.
They documented the installation of Grecia's new beak and recorded a documentary, Toucan Country, which aired on Animal Planet this month.
The documentary "Toucan Country" shows how a small toucan can make a difference in a country and how it can get its citizens involved in the fight against animal cruelty.
Key takeaway: Japanese oil companies are particularly wary of the rise of China's small, independent refineries, known as "teapots".
Reference News Network reported on August 12 that Japanese media said that JX Energy, Japan's largest oil company, believes that "the expansion of China's exports is one of the reasons for the downturn."
Japanese oil companies, in particular, are wary of the rise of small, independent refineries in China, known as "teapots."
The quality of China's petroleum products is gradually approaching that of Japanese oil products due to the Chinese government's tightening of environmental regulations.
Before obtaining a crude oil import license, "teapot refineries" generally imported heavy oil with a higher sulfur content from Russia and other places for refining.
The sulfur content of the petroleum products produced is high, and the oil products are not good, which has become one of the causes of environmental pollution.
After obtaining a crude oil import permit, the "teapot refinery" was able to import Omani crude oil with a lower sulfur content and Russian crude oil, and the quality of its petroleum products also improved.
"With the continuous improvement of China's domestic petroleum product quality standards, the capacity of oil refining equipment has also improved.
As a result, the quality of China's petroleum products exported to the outside world has gradually reached the same level as Japan's, which is of the highest quality in the world."
"After the end of 2015, China began exporting high-quality light oil to Australia," JX Energy said, competing with Japanese products in the Asian market.
Although "Japan Premium Oil" is facing a crisis, the strategy adopted by Japanese oil companies is only to "pay attention to market conditions while exporting to profitable regions".
Due to the huge impact of China's petroleum exports on the Asian market, there is a growing interest in teapot refineries.
