According to the Bureau of Statistics, New Zealand's population growth had previously only exceeded 2 per cent during the peak of the "baby boom" population in 1974 and the early '50s and '60s.
As of June this year, New Zealand's net inflow of migrants in the 12-month period was 69,100, becoming the main driver of New Zealand's population growth in recent years.
In addition, the natural increase in New Zealand's population during the same time period was 28,200.
The data shows that in the last 10 years, New Zealand has an average annual net inflow of 21,800 immigrants, and the average annual natural increase in population is 32,300.
In terms of demographics, the influx of migrants means that the proportion of the "working-age population" between the ages of 15 and 39 is gradually expanding.
In the 12 months to June 2016, New Zealand's working-age population grew by 3.6 per cent to 1.58 million.
At the same time, the number of people over the age of 65 also increased by 3.6% to 700,000.
