Ultraviolet rays not only darken the skin of students, but also sunburn their skin, how to make the skin survive the military training smoothly and not be sunburned?
Sunscreen packaging is generally marked with SPF and PA, SPF refers to the sun protection index, which is against UVB ultraviolet rays, and our common SPF index is 15, 30, 50, etc.
Products marked with PA are for UVA, so that the sunscreen will play a more effective role, usually, the strength of PA is expressed by +, and one more + means that the effective protection time is extended.
For oily skin, you should choose a water-based sunscreen with strong penetration, and sunscreen spray is also a good choice.
For dry skin, choose a cream-like sunscreen; Normal skin generally has no strict rules, and it is a burden for sensitive skin to wear any skin care products, so it is recommended to choose pure physical sunscreen products.
Remember to apply sunscreen half an hour in advance, as it takes time for sunscreen products to fully penetrate into the skin.
Military training has a long time of sun exposure, and sunscreen can be wiped every two hours to have a lasting effect, so don't be lazy.
Because the skin has just been irritated by the sun, do not use whitening products immediately after returning from military training.
After military training and exposure, if possible, you can use a towel wrapped in ice cubes to cool the burned skin to relieve local heat.
