After the upgrade, the old Wanfu River and the Beida slip channel of the Beijing-Hangzhou Grand Canal branch channel will be charged tolls from September 1.
The two tributary waterways have been renovated and constructed in the form of social financing, and the fees have been approved by the relevant departments of the provincial government.
The Laowanfu River channel flows through Jinxiang and Yutai, and enters the main channel of the Beijing-Hangzhou Grand Canal through Nanyang Lake, with a total length of 32.5 kilometers.
According to the needs of navigation, the Laowanfu River channel has adopted the method of maintenance and transformation, dredging the local water depth, cutting and straightening the local sharp bends, etc., and the navigation conditions have been improved.
The waterway flows through Jinxiang County and Rencheng District, and enters the main channel of the Beijing-Hangzhou Grand Canal through Nanyang Lake, with a total length of 19 kilometers.
The reconstruction project of the two waterways started construction in February 2011 and completed the delivery and acceptance in January 2015.
In accordance with the principle of "loan construction, fee repayment", Jining Anping Canal Logistics Service Center collects waterway tolls according to the charging standards approved by the Shandong Provincial Price Bureau.
Among them, the basic toll is charged at 1.75 yuan/deadweight ton, and the mileage toll is charged at 0.05 yuan/kilometer deadweight ton.
Tolls are collected from June 15, 2016 to June 14, 2019.
The reporter learned from the Jining Port and Shipping Bureau that there are currently four toll waterways in Jining, namely the Zhushui River Channel, the Baima River Channel, the Beida Slip Channel, and the Laowanfu River Channel.
The four waterways are tributaries of the Beijing-Hangzhou Grand Canal, all of which have been upgraded through social financing.
The Zhushui River Waterway Upgrading Project is the first project to adopt the "government + market" model for the construction of inland port and shipping infrastructure in Shandong Province, with the government accounting for the main investment and social funds to supplement the funding gap.
The Baima River, the Laowanfu River, the Beidatao River and other feeder waterways adopt a purely market-oriented operation mode.
The funds allocated by the state treasury cannot meet the needs of the construction of the project, which restricts the progress of the upgrading of the waterway.
The use of social funds for the construction of public infrastructure meets the requirements of national policies and has also become a way to break the bottleneck of funds.
