The Greenland shark, also known as the small-headed sleeping shark, is widely distributed in the North Atlantic waters around Greenland and Iceland, reaching a length of 4 to 5 meters when it reaches adulthood.
However, their growth rate is extremely slow, sometimes only about 1 centimeter per year, suggesting that Greenland sharks may have an exceptionally long lifespan.
Traditional dating methods usually use calcified tissue from animals, and in some sharks fins, but this calcified tissue is scarce in Greenland sharks.
New research, led by Julius Nelson of the University of Copenhagen in Denmark, switched to radiocarbon dating using the eye lens of Greenland sharks.
This method has been used to determine the age of whales before, but this is the first time it has been used to determine the age of fish such as sharks.
Their analysis showed that the largest shark had an estimated lifespan of 392 years, with an error of 120 years.
This means that the shark is at least 272 years old, and the maximum is likely to be 512 years old.
In addition, female Greenland sharks are said to be not sexually mature until they are about 4 metres long, which translates to at least 156 years of age.
The Greenland shark is the longest-lived vertebrate known on Earth, surpassing the previous longevity champion right whale (211 years old), the researchers wrote in the paper.
