The congressional panel said military officials distorted ISIS intelligence
Officials at U.S. Central Command changed intelligence reports to paint a more optimistic picture of the war against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than it actually was, a congressional panel noted in a report released Thursday.
The interim report comes from a task force formed by Republican chairs of the House Armed Services Committee, the Intelligence Committee and the Defense Subcommittee of the House Appropriations Committee. The report said there was "widespread discontent" among CENTCOM intelligence analysts who said their superiors were tampering with their assessments of the U.S. war against the Islamic State.
Central Command (Centcom) in Tampa, Florida, is the military headquarters responsible for overseeing U.S. military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
According to a news release on the report, "Intelligence reviewed by senior CENTCOM leaders portrays more optimistic about U.S. counterterrorism operations than they actually do, and consistently more optimistic than analyses by other intelligence agencies." ”
The California Republican representative said: "The behavior of CENTCOM is unacceptable. On one side, our fighters are suffering from war, and on the other side are high-level policymakers receiving misanalysis. ”
The question of the leadership of CENTCOM has extended to the highest levels of the agency.
The report details long-standing problems with CENTCOM in 2014 and 2015 in describing and analyzing U.S. training of Iraqi troops.
While there is no conclusive evidence that senior officials in the Obama administration ordered changes to the reports, according to the report's description, the analysts felt pressured by CENTCOM leaders to voice a more optimistic opinion about the threat posed by the Islamic State (ISIS or ISIL).
"In the first half of 2015, many CENTCOM press releases, statements and congressional testimony were much more optimistic than they actually did," the report said. ”
For example, a Central Command official has publicly stated that a major military operation could be taken to retake Mosul as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq's second-largest city, remains under the control of ISIS.
Representative Mike Pompeo, Republican of Kansas, said in a statement: "After months of investigation, this result is clear. ”
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, most senior intelligence officers at U.S. Central Command manipulated the command's intelligence products to conceal the threat of the Islamic State in Iraq.
After Republicans learned from analysts that intelligence about the Islamic State had been manipulated, they set up a task force.
As the investigation continues, more discoveries will follow the report released on Thursday.
The Prosecutor General of the Ministry of Defense has also conducted a long-term investigation into CENTCOM.
Democratic members of the House Intelligence Committee released their findings on Thursday, consistent with some of the conclusions of the Republican task force.
In a statement, the Democratic leader of the committee, Mr. Shea, said that between 2014 and 2015, CENTCOM developed an overly narrow process for intelligence assessments of Islamic State and Iraqi peacekeepers. ”
Mr. Cheada said the process "hampered the release of intelligence," lowered analysts' morale and "made it "unacceptable to dissenting opinions." ”
But Mr. Cheah and the Democrats also said they had found no evidence that the White House was trying to put pressure on CENTCOM analysts when their conclusions fit "presuppositions or political narratives." ”
The Daily Beast reported on Tuesday the preliminary findings of the congressional investigation.
Last August, the New York Times reported that the Pentagon's attorney general began an investigation after receiving complaints from CENTCOM analysts.
Pentagon spokesman Navy Rear Adm. Patrick Evans said in a statement that the Defense Department would not make any comments on the congressional report until the attorney general's investigation was concluded.
But "experts sometimes disagree on the interpretation of complex data, and intelligence agencies and the Department of Defense encourage healthy conversations on these important national security topics," he said. ”
The impact of the investigation has outweighed the question of whether the U.S.-led bombing campaigns in Iraq and Syria have succeeded, as a growing number of Defense Department officials claim.
But last year, those claims raised questions about the extent to which President Ma could trust CENTCOM's assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis areas.
Criticism of Islamic State intelligence is reminiscent of the controversy more than a decade ago, when CENTCOM intelligence analyst Gregory Hook wrote a research article in which George W. Bush's administration insisted on sending small forces to Iraq despite the opposition of many analysts and gave little thought to what happened after the 2003 invasion.
Mr. Hook played a key role in the campaign against ISIS intelligence.
Last year, officials said Mr. Hook's team had concluded that the airstrikes against the Islamic State refinery had not significantly reduced the terrorist group's economic revenues, as the group had built makeshift refineries to continue selling oil on the black market, contrary to the statements made.
According to a September report by Time Magazine, CENTCOM did not make the findings public.
Central Command Commander Lloyd Austin III was criticized last year after lawyers reviewed Senate testimony about overly optimistic assessments of the war.
General Austin retired in April and is currently replaced by Joseph Wattle in his position at CENTCOM.
