The shabby food of the Great Depression in "The Hearty Meal".
In March 1933, Franklin J. Brown, who had just been elected president, was elected president of the People's Republic of China. Delano Roosevelt sat in the president's office for lunch.
As a foodie, President Roosevelt loved Fifth Avenue food, like foie gras and Maryland fish stew.
On that day, his menu was simple: devil eggs with tomato sauce, mashed potatoes and preserved pudding as a snack.
Jen Ziegman said: "It's about sharing the joys and sorrows of people who are suffering when it comes to food. ”
Her husband, Andrew Coe, added: "It's also a reflection of the American way of eating. ”
The husband and wife, who live in Brooklyn Heights, are both food historians.
Mr. Ko's last book, "Stir-fried Chowder," was about Chinese food in the United States, and Ms. Ziegman's book, "97 Orchards," tells the story of the lives of slum tenants through food.
Their new book, "The Feast," will be published Tuesday by Harper, which is about food history in the United States during the Great Depression.
After presenting some common insights on food, they met a reporter at Eisenberg's sandwich shop. This simple lunch counter in the Flatiron District has been open since 1929, when the economy was in a downturn.
Ms. Ziegman, 54, ordered a sandwich with cream cheese and crushed olives, while Mr. Ko, 57, ordered a platter of turkey, mashed potatoes and vegetables.
The reporter ordered a baked meat wrap, which the couple thought was appropriate to discuss the diet of the Great Depression.
"Bread was very popular at the time," says Ms. Ziegman. ”
At that time, there were peanut bread, liver bread, and soy bread.
They are all made with one ingredient and a cheap topping that can be poured over the ingredient.
Imagine that your dinner is all peanuts.
Mr. Coe put on a strange look.
"They must be like lead in your stomach," he said. ”
In the years leading up to the Great Depression, Americans had a buffet, especially in the suburbs.
A group of women cook for the male farm workers, and there are freshly punched pies for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.
In World War I, it was the Americans who gave food to hungry Europeans. "The Feast" chronicles how the country suddenly ceased to be a land of abundance.
Mr. Coe explains why he and his wife wrote the book: "At that time, food had become a major topic of displeasure for Americans. ”
Another unpleasant topic was shabby new foods: "mystery foods" such as bread and stews became the main course, and stews were "the best way to cook leftovers," Ms. Ziegman said, because chefs could use cream in sauces to mask unpalatable ingredients.
Fresh fruits are replaced by cheap dried fruits.
Meat, which has been the protagonist of the American table for many years, has become a rare luxury.
A strange hodgepodge of calories, nutrition is the first thing people think about over taste or even basic cooking knowledge.
While researching the book, including various recipes, Ms. Ziegman made a roasted onion stuffed with peanut oil.
"It's not very common at dinner tables," Mr. Coe said. ”
"It's also weird," Ms. Ziegman said.
Peanut oil doesn't go well with roasted onions at all.
This is characteristic of many family budget meals.
Household economists such as Louis Stanley, who served as chef of the Federal Directorate for the Family Economy from 1923 to 1943, influenced the country's eating habits for the first time in history.
They publish recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines that encourage women to be "budget-conscious" and brave enough to turn bad foods like creamy pasta with carrots into gourmets.
