During the Cold War, the Soviet Union brought missiles into Cuba, almost leading to a nuclear war between the United States and the Soviet Union.
This event is regarded as the pinnacle of the Cold War, and history is known as the "Cuban Missile Crisis".
But what is less well known is that a powerful solar storm during the Cold War also threatened to cause a nuclear war in the United States against the Soviet Union, an event that was not first made public by researchers until August 9.
On May 23, 1967, a severe solar storm caused intense interference to the U.S. military's radar and radio communications in the North Pole.
These radars were part of the American ballistic missile warning system and were used to monitor Soviet missiles.
The paper, completed by researchers at the University of Colorado, interviewed U.S. military personnel involved in forecasting and analyzing solar activity at the time, as well as reviewing unclassified literature.
The paper writes that in the 60s of the last century, in order to prevent the Soviet Union from suddenly launching a nuclear war, the US Air Force always had some fighters with nuclear warheads flying in the sky.
Unaware that the main culprit of the interference was a solar storm and not the Soviet Union, the U.S. military commander ordered the fighter jets to be put into combat readiness.
Fortunately, the US military's solar activity, which began in the late 50s of the last century and its study of electromagnetic interference from the Earth, finally prevented this potential military conflict.
Later, he summarized the information provided by the Aviation Meteorological Service of the US Air Force and submitted a detailed report.
As a direct consequence of the solar storm, the U.S. military has since viewed space weather as an operational concern and has established a more robust space weather forecasting system.
