The report is divided into nine chapters, including overall policy adjustment, military strength, national defense budget, military deployment, weaponry, institutional reform, military training and exercises, foreign military security cooperation, and military security relations with China.
According to the report, 2015 was the final year of the Abe administration's major policy adjustments in the security sector for several consecutive years.
Since then, Japan's measures in the field of security will mainly focus on the operational aspects of the application of the legal system, the implementation of strategies, and the implementation of policies, rather than the drastic adjustment and change of frameworks, mechanisms, and policies.
The report stresses that the Abe cabinet is trying to achieve the multiple goals of promoting Japan's "normal nationalization", the Self-Defense Forces going out to intervene in international security affairs, strengthening the Japan-US alliance, and preventing and containing China through the above three breakthroughs.
Previously, the China Association for the Promotion of Strategic Culture released Japan's military strength assessment reports on June 5, 2012, July 19, 2013, July 23, 2014, and June 30, 2015.
