The future of the Portland smelter is fraught with uncertainty due to the cancellation of the power supply contract
The Portland Aluminium Smelter in Victoria, along with hundreds of workers at the plant, is currently facing an uncertain future after the power company that powers the plant revealed that a plant owner would terminate a supply contract, invalidating all supply contracts.
This move comes after the Victorian government decided not to continue with subsidies to guarantee the operation of the plant.
The 20-year fixed subsidy will expire in November.
Alcoa's Portland plant of 2,000 workers could face losing their jobs.
Once the factory is closed, up to 2,000 people could lose their jobs, either directly or indirectly.
And since the plant accounts for about 10 per cent of Victoria's total electricity output, there could be a ripple effect.
In 2014, Alcoa shut down the Hanrui Point smelter, which led to the closure of the Anglesey Island power plant last year.
Alcoa's Portland smelter is currently losing money and is at risk of closure.
The move follows forecasts for the next few years at the plant, initially due to the strengthening of the Australian dollar and more recently because of the price of the plant's products.
AGL is powering the large aluminium smelter through the Laoe Eyan Power Plant in the Latrobe Valley. The company predicts that three other plant owners will also terminate their agreements.
The plant's largest shareholder is a joint venture between Alcoa and Alumina, while China's CITIC Group and Japan's Marubeni Corp. also hold minority shares.
"AGL expects the Portland plant to continue to operate, meaning the smelter will continue to generate electricity demand," the joint venture said. ”
AGL said the contracts were "hedging contracts" that were supposed to be in effect from November 2016.
The termination period of the contracts is 12 months, so they will be terminated in 2017.
"As a result, AGL still expects these contracts to continue to generate revenue in FY2017," the utility said. ”
Any potential revenue impact on AGL from FY2018 onwards is currently driven by the futures market's optimistic outlook for wholesale electricity prices.
AGL said it had written down $187 million of the contract value in "end-of-life expectations".
Alcoa said the decision to terminate the contracts "will not affect Alcoa's ability to operate the smelter or guarantee the smelter's power supply."
The U.S. company said it signed a 20-year contract with Mr. Eyan in 2010 that was supposed to take effect in November, but it did not explain why it was withdrawing from the contract.
Analysts are cautious about whether the Portland smelter in Victoria and the Tomago plant near Newcastle will close due to the industry's dire economic situation.
In response to analysts' comments earlier this week, AGL's head of operations, Stephen Mickelson, said Portland uses about 600 megawatts of electricity annually and the Tomago plant reaches about 900 megawatts.
If two plants are closed, the demand in the electricity market will be greatly reduced.
"As an electric company, this is not good news for us," he said.
