NASA climate model: Venus was once habitable
According to NASA's new climate model, Venus was once habitable.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model that explores Venus's past, using tools and algorithms very similar to those used by climate scientists.
This model is used to determine whether Venus, which has a hot surface, no water, and an atmosphere full of carbon dioxide, has ever had an environment similar to Earth.
Previously, scientists thought that Venus's slower rotation was due to its thicker atmosphere.
But the latest simulations suggest that Venus may have had a thinner, Earth-like atmosphere at one time, and that its rotation was similarly slower at the time.
The model also shows the early topography of Venus.
Venus may have more dry regions than Earth, but there was once enough water and geographic change to nurture life and prevent rapid evaporation.
In the early days, the sunlight shining on Venus was 30% dimmer than on Earth.
Anthony del Genio, a scientist at the Goddard Institute for Space Studies, explained at a press conference: "In the model simulations of the Goddard Institute for Space Studies, the slow rotation of Venus makes one side of the day last for almost two months. ”
This warms the surface and produces rain that forms thick clouds that act like an umbrella to block most of the sun's heat from the ground.
The results of the simulations showed that the average climate temperature of Venus was actually a few degrees lower than that of the Earth today.
The model simulates the evolution of Venus similar to what previous planetary scientists had speculated.
Although life may have existed on Venus, it has been exposed to excessive temperatures and ultraviolet rays over the course of billions of years.
The planet's oceans evaporate, and water vapor is burned out by ultraviolet rays.
As hydrogen escaped, all that was left was a thicker atmosphere of carbon dioxide and deadly greenhouse gas effects, thus forming the planet we know today.
The researchers published the simulation results of a new Venus climate model in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
