Kepler measures the rotation speed of the stars of the Pleiades star cluster
The Kepler Space Telescope's latest mission has helped astronomers capture the most complete sequence of star rotation velocities in the Pleiades star cluster.
The new data is helping astronomers understand why the cluster's stars have different rotation speeds and how the rotation period correlates with the composition of the planets.
Lusa Rabre, a research scientist at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at the California Institute of Technology in Pasadena, said at a press conference: "We hope to better understand the relationship between star mass, age, and even the history of the solar system by comparing our results with other star clusters. ”
The Pleiades star cluster is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster were born about 125 million years ago and are still in their adult stages.
They reach the highest rotation speed in their lifetime.
At their maximum rotation speed, these mature stars emit a large number of stellar winds.
When these stellar winds pass through the star's magnetic field, they act as a brake on the star.
As the age of the star increases, its rotation begins to slow down.
Kepler measured the rotation speed of each star by tracking the time of the appearance of recognizable star sunspots, such as sunspots.
The latest dataset of rotational velocity indicates that the rotation speed of the more massive stars is slower than that of the less massive stars.
Rabul likens the stars to dancers, with larger dancers spinning slower than smaller dancers.
"In the 'ballet' of the Pleiades star cluster, we found that stars with slower rotation tend to be more massive, while those with the fastest rotation tend to be the lightest," Rabul said. ”
Due to the close proximity of the Pleiades star cluster, it can be used as an ideal cosmic laboratory to compare the mass of stars with their rotation speed.
